Class DT_Abstract1

  • java.lang.Object
    • DT_Abstract1
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DT_Abstract2

    public abstract class DT_Abstract1
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    This class begins the definition of a Domain Theory in Prolog syntax. In this system, a Domain Theory is a grammar defining a Kinship System. This is the level at which 90% of the action takes place in Active Learning.

    Because so many methods are defined at the Domain Theory level, the code files are broken into 4 classes: DT_Abstract1, DT_Abstract12, & DomainTheory.

                         java.lang.String sex)
                           throws KSBadHornClauseException,
                                  JavaSystemException,
                                  KSInternalErrorException,
                                  KSConstraintInconsistency,
                                  KSNoChainOfRelations2Alter,
                                  java.lang.ClassNotFoundException
        Create a GEDCOM file containing hypothetical people who illustrate each definition of each kinTerm in this Domain Theory.
        Parameters:
        fileName - the filename to create in GEDCOM format.
        sex - the gender of Ego in the hypothetical population
        Throws:
        KSBadHornClauseException - if a clause is encountered for which it cannot create an example
        JavaSystemException - if Java throws a run-time exception
        KSInternalErrorException - if an internal processing activity occurs
        KSConstraintInconsistency - if the constraints on a person (imposed by the literals in a clause) are inconsistent. For example: male(X) and female(X).
        KSNoChainOfRelations2Alter - if a clause is encountered with no "path" from Ego to Alter via its literals. For example: 'foo(Alter,Ego) :- parent(P,Ego), child(Alter,Q).' is wrong. But 'foo(Alter,Ego) :- parent(P,Ego), sibling(P,Q), child(Alter,Q).' is OK.
        java.lang.ClassNotFoundException

                           throws KSBadHornClauseException,

                                  java.lang.ClassNotFoundException
        Create a GEDCOM file containing hypothetical people who illustrate each definition of each kinTerm in this Domain Theory.
        Parameters:
        fileName - the filename to create in GEDCOM format.
        sex - the gender of Ego in the hypothetical population
        hypo - the hypothetical context.
        options - If it contains 'theory' then a file will be written with a full expansion of this domain theory and some diagnostic information. If it contains 'census' then a printable listing of all Individuals and Families will be written to a file.
        Throws:
        KSBadHornClauseException - if a clause is encountered for which it cannot create an example
        JavaSystemException - if Java throws a run-time exception
        KSInternalErrorException - if an internal processing activity occurs
        KSConstraintInconsistency - if the constraints on a person (imposed by the literals in a clause) are inconsistent. For example: male(X) and female(X).
        KSNoChainOfRelations2Alter - if a clause is encountered with no "path" from Ego to Alter via its literals. For example: 'foo(Alter,Ego) :- parent(P,Ego), child(Alter,Q).' is wrong. But 'foo(Alter,Ego) :- parent(P,Ego), sibling(P,Q), child(Alter,Q).' is OK.
        java.lang.ClassNotFoundException
